				<img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/954e990f86d575cec9b36135fe273d2f?s=44&amp;d=identicon&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-44 photo' height='44' width='44' /><cite><b class="fn">Zac Gochenour</b> </cite><a href="http://elidourado.com/blog/austrian-macro-right-and-wrong/#comment-1861"><time datetime="2011-08-31T18:08:05+00:00">August 31, 2011 at 6:08 pm</time></a>			</header><!-- .comment-meta -->

			
			<section class="comment-content comment">
				<p>Actually it&#8217;s hard to say what &#8220;Austrian Macro&#8221; really is. Hayek actually used the constant-MV norm to criticize the gold standard, which a lot of Austrians like. Kirzner is a critic of the &#8220;Austrian&#8221; business cycle:<br />
<blockquote>KIRZNER: No, I’ve never had too much interest in the Austrian business cycle theory. I’ve never felt that the Hayekian business cycle theory was essentially Austrian. In fact, Mises, who was the originator of this whole idea in 1912, didn’t see it as particularly Austrian either. There are passages where he notes that people call it the Austrian theory, but he says it’s not really Austrian. It goes back to the Currency School and Knut Wicksell. It’s certainly not historically Austrian. Further, I would claim that, as developed by Hayek, there are many aspects of it that are non-Austrian. I don’t believe that to be an Austrian you have to buy into the Hayekian view of business cycles.</p></blockquote>
<p>More from Kirzner <a href="http://socialdemocracy21stcentury.blogspot.com/2011/05/kirzner-on-austrian-business-cycle.html" rel="nofollow">here</a>.</p>
<p>So this is really the Wicksellian theory (see the great Leijonhufvud piece &#8220;<a href="http://www.econ.ucla.edu/workingpapers/wp165.pdf" rel="nofollow">The Wicksell Connection</a>&#8220;) which Hayek expounded on in Prices and Production. The Wicksellian point is that expansionary monetary policy affects the &#8220;savings-investment&#8221; nexus and effects structural changes, where capital is treated as a heterogenous good, and that&#8217;s what drives the prediction that these changes will have such large effects on the economy. You have not just cyclical risk but long term risk from malinvestment. So Hayek wanted to avoid non-zero excess demands for goods arising from money hoarding or dishoarding.</p>
<p>So, what is right and wrong about this story, I largely agree with the critiques made by you, Caplan, Cowen, Sumner. I think an Austrian business cycle is possible in theory but not supported by empirical evidence as a sufficient explanation for existing cycles. Policy wise, maybe we can all agree that stabilizing NGDP would be a good thing, although folks like White and Garrison express doubts that the fed can do it (and doubt that Sumner&#8217;s prediction market would work).</p>
							</section><!-- .comment-content -->

			<div class="reply">
							</div><!-- .reply -->
		</article><!-- #comment-## -->
	</li><!-- #comment-## -->
		</ol><!-- .commentlist -->

		
		
	
						
